      <hedline>
        <hl1>Environmental Effects Of Wood-Fired Boilers</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Fred Schmitt letter on Peter Iwanowicz's February 4 Op-Ed article on environmental problems connected with wood-burning boilers</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>As a chronic asthmatic, I can't thank you enough for bringing the problem of wood-burning boilers and stoves to the forefront (''Smoke Signals,'' by Peter M. Iwanowicz, Op-Ed, Feb. 4).</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>As a chronic asthmatic, I can't thank you enough for bringing the problem of wood-burning boilers and stoves to the forefront (''Smoke Signals,'' by Peter M. Iwanowicz, Op-Ed, Feb. 4).</p>
        <p>If anyone thinks it is properly ''green'' to use these monstrosities without proper emission controls, they are mistaken, for they, too, are contributing to global warming and are polluting our air with noxious, carcinogenic emissions, as well as harming millions of us who suffer with pulmonary conditions.</p>
        <p>I cannot understand how our elected officials can continue to ignore this growing threat to our environment.</p>
        <p>Fred Schmitt  Northport, N.Y.</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
